sec.p:
Based on the results of the study, the following conclusions can be inferred:


The applied standard liquids indicated differences in the values of the contact angles, determined for the examined fabrics by the DCA and Washburn methods; however, the mean SFE values obtained in the Wu and van Oss–Chaudhury–Good models did not show significant differences for the tested fabrics;

The values of SFE for fabrics A, B and C, different in their structure, with the 50:50 ratio of raw material composition of polyimide amide/viscose, were close to the mean value of energy determined for homogeneous fabric D (100% of polyimide amide) and E (100% of viscose);

Both methods of the contact angle measurements (DCA and W) are useful in determining the fabric SFE;

The applied version of the Washburn method for measuring the contact angles showed its high applicability in assessing fiber surface properties in fabrics used in this study (regardless of their structure);

The DCA method allows for a better observation of the effect exerted by the fabric structure of the same raw material composition on wettability. It can be also useful in predicting the utility/barrier properties of fabrics;

More experimental data obtained with the use of model fabrics is needed for proper designing of protective textiles in the future.
